item.description:
arXiv:2412.19956v2 Announce Type: replace 
Abstract: For $0 < \alpha \leq 1$, let $E$ be a compact subset of the $d$-dimensional moment curve in $\mathbb{R}^d$ such that $N(E,\varepsilon) \lesssim \varepsilon^{-\alpha}$ for $0 <\varepsilon <1$ where $N(E,\varepsilon)$ is the smallest number of $\varepsilon$-balls needed to cover $E$. We proved that if $f \in L^p(\mathbb{R}^d)$ with \begin{align*}
  1 \leq p\leq p_\alpha:=
  \begin{cases}
  \frac{d^2+d+2\alpha}{2\alpha} & d \geq 3,
  \frac{4}{\alpha} &d =2,
  \end{cases}
  \end{align*} and $\widehat{f}$ is supported on the set $E$, then $f$ is identically zero. We also proved that the range of $p$ is optimal by considering random Cantor sets on the moment curve. We extended the result of Guo, Iosevich, Zhang and Zorin-Kranich, including the endpoint. We also considered applications of our results to the failure of the restriction estimates and Wiener Tauberian Theorem.
